nd understand existing patterns before making changes.\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n**ADP Phases:** Explore → Specify → Test → Implement → Verify → Document\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n### Phase 0: Explore\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n- Read all files in the affected area of the codebase.\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n- Identify existing patterns, naming conventions, and architectural decisions.\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n- Review related tests to understand expected behavior.\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n- Update progress.md with exploration findings.\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n### Phase 1: Specify\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n- Write a specification to `specs/t-022@20260416t054258z-spec.md`.\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n- Include: problem statement, technical approach, edge cases, acceptance criteria.\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n- Each acceptance criterion must have a VERIFY command.\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n### Phase 2: Test Development\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n- Write tests BEFORE implementation, derived from the specification.\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n- Tests must FAIL before implementation (Red phase).\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n- After this phase, test files are LOCKED — do not modify assertions.\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n### Phase 3: Implement\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n- Implement the minimum code needed to pass all tests.\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n- One sub-task at a time, commit each logical unit.\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n- Type hints on all function signatures.\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n- Follow existing patterns.\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n### Phase 4: Verify & Document\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n- Run full test suite and quality checks.\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n- Update CHANGELOG.md, progress.md.\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n## Rules\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n- No questions — document assumptions in ESCALATIONS.md.\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n- Do not modify locked test assertions.\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n- Log new dependencies to ESCALATIONS.md.\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n- Commit per sub-task: `feat(scope): summary [T-022@20260416T054258Z]`\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n## Common Pitfalls (from recurring verify feedback)\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\nThese are the top reasons tasks get PASS WITH NOTES instead of clean PASS.\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\nAvoid them on the first attempt:\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n- **Always include a migration** when adding or modifying database columns.\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n  A new model or column without a migration is a deployment gap.\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n- **Commit all changes** before the verify phase begins. Uncommitted work\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n  is flagged as blocking by the verifier.\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n- **Stay in scope** — only commit work under this task's ID. Do not bundle\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n  changes from adjacent subtasks or refactor unrelated code.\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n- **Add indexes on new FK columns** in `__table_args__` when adding\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n  foreign key relationships.\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n- **Keep CHANGELOG entries consistent** with actual behavior. Do not copy\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n  descriptions from other tasks or specs without verifying they match\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n  the implemented code.\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n## Validation\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\nRun before final commit:\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n```bash\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\npip install -e '.[dev]' && pytest tests/ -x && ruff check src/ tests/ && mypy src/\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n```\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\nAll must pass.\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n## Candidate Hardening (Auto-Generated)\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\nUse the recurring failure patterns below as mandatory hardening checks:\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n- Address this recurring failure mode explicitly: Runtime does not invoke bootstrap_identity on startup, so the identity file is never guaranteed to be created automatically at first run. Severity: blocking.\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n- Address this recurring failure mode explicitly: Add bootstrap_identity() invocation in startup flow (before FirstBootAnnouncer) so first boots mint and persist identity automatically..\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n- Address this recurring failure mode explicitly: Ensure th