sdp/verification/t-016@20260427t001208z-verify.md:21:4. **Graceful SIGTERM** — Signal handler sets `stop_event`; `asyncio.wait(FIRST_COMPLETED)` unblocks; `worker_task.cancel()` is called in `finally`. Minor note: cancellation interrupts at the next `await` checkpoint (inside `_generate_async`), not strictly after the in-flight item fully completes. In the idle case (no queued work) this is exact. For active-generation scenarios the cancel lands mid-item rather than after the item — semantically slightly weaker than the spec wording, but acceptable for a background worker and consistent with Python async cancellation conventions.
sdp/verification/t-016@20260427t001208z-verify.md:56:- [ ] In-flight item not guaranteed to complete on SIGTERM — `worker_task.cancel()` interrupts at the next `await` checkpoint rather than after the current item finishes. Affects long-running Replicate API calls. Severity: minor (tests pass; idle path matches spec; full-item drain would require a stop-flag plumbed into `_worker_loop`).
sdp/verification/t-016@20260427t001208z-verify.md:63:1. The "finishes current item" semantic is currently "cancels at next await checkpoint". If future work requires true item-drain-on-SIGTERM (e.g. for long Replicate predictions), consider plumbing a `stop_requested: asyncio.Event` into `_worker_loop` so it exits cleanly after `_process_next_async` returns rather than receiving `CancelledError` mid-call.
